data.content:
## EF Core Cosmos DB Provider: Sync-over-Async Removed in .NET 11

In .NET 10, the Cosmos DB provider let you opt into **sync-over-async** (wrapping async SDK calls in blocking `.Result`/`.Wait()`). In .NET 11 (EF Core 11), **that opt-in is removed entirely**. Every synchronous LINQ operator — `ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, and `SaveChanges()` — will throw an `InvalidOperationException` at runtime.

### Why it was removed
The underlying Cosmos DB SDK is **async-only**. Sync-over-async wrappers risk **deadlocks** and **thread-pool starvation**, especially under load in ASP.NET Core.

### What to do
Convert every call to its async counterpart:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

### Key changes
| .NET 10 (sync-over-async) | .NET 11 (async required) |
|---|---|
| `ToList()` | `ToListAsync()` |
| `First()` / `Single()` | `FirstAsync()` / `SingleAsync()` |
| `Count()` / `Any()` | `CountAsync()` / `AnyAsync()` |
| `SaveChanges()` | `SaveChangesAsync()` |

You'll need to propagate `async/await` up the call chain (controllers, services, etc.). This is the intended path — the Cosmos SDK was never synchronous, so the sync facade was always a compatibility shim.
